<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-624-792  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 624 792.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Byte  July 1990 v15 n7 p105(3).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Networks shouldn't be this hard. (users should demand easier localarea network set-up and configuration) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Van Name, Mark L.; Catchings, Bill.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Local area network (LAN) users must demand that MS-DOS personalcomputer (PC) vendors, LAN hardware makers and LAN operatingsystem (OS) and client software publishers provide networks thatare easier to implement in the PC environment.andP;  The PCarchitecture does not automatically recognize add-in boards, andboard drivers and LAN OS must be installed and configured toaccess network resources.andP;  There are also many PC LAN productalternatives, which makes LAN selection, installation,configuration and running a more complicated process than that inthe unitary Apple Macintosh environment.andP;  The situation can beimproved by PC vendors installing and configuring network adaptersand adding LAN chips to motherboards and network access to theAUTOEXEC.BAT file.andP;  LAN OS vendors could simplify configuration,load the network adapter device driver at run time, andstandardize client software.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     ImplementationRequirements AnalysisProblem ComplexityPerformance ImprovementLocal area networks (Computer networks).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>